===Etymology===
Commonly linked by [[folk etymology]] to {{cog|la|niger||black}}, which likely influenced the modern spelling. Some sources give the term to {{etyl|tmh|en}} roots, deriving it from a claimed ''gher n-gheren'' or ''egereou n-igereouen'' ("river of rivers").<ref name=meek1960>C. K. Meek, [http://www.jstor.org/stable/179702 The Niger and the Classics: The History of a Name]. The Journal of African History. Vol. 1, No. 1 (1960), pp. 1-17</ref><ref>[http://www.etymonline.com/index.php?term=Niger&allowed_in_frame=0 "Niger", ''Online Etymology Dictionary'']</ref> Older sources derive ''Niger'' via a series of mistranslations and geographic misplacements by Greek, Roman and Arab geographers, from Ptolemy's descriptions of the valley Gir (a wadi in modern Algeria), and the "Lower Gir" (or "Ni-Gir") to the south.<ref>G. Long, "Niger", ''The penny cyclopædia''</ref>

